<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chiquitensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea chiquitensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a distinctive species readily recognised by the very small, shortly pedunculate flowers, adaxially pilose leaves and small pointed pilose sepals. The small glabrous pink corolla (c. 2.2 cm long) is only matched by that of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dumetorum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. dumetorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="deminuta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. deminuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and some species in the 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Liliopsida" family="Eriospermaceae" genus="Batatas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Batatas</taxonomicName>
Clade (A3), such as 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ramosissima">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. ramosissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but is readily distinguished from all of these by the distinctive ovate, acute sepals.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
